00:00:21.300 --> 00:00:24.430
PROFESSOR: Good afternoon.

00:00:24.430 --> 00:00:26.310
Let's get started.

00:00:28.920 --> 00:00:32.189
So we continue our
discussion today

00:00:32.189 --> 00:00:35.320
about light atom interaction.

00:00:35.320 --> 00:00:38.952
And just to sort of
remind you where we are,

00:00:38.952 --> 00:00:43.410
we started last week,
even before spring

00:00:43.410 --> 00:00:47.620
break, to talk about
the matrix element which

00:00:47.620 --> 00:00:49.410
provides a coupling.

00:00:49.410 --> 00:00:52.090
So now we have a coupling
between the two states.

00:00:52.090 --> 00:00:54.150
And we want to
understand what is

00:00:54.150 --> 00:00:56.990
the coupling doing
to the system.

00:00:56.990 --> 00:00:59.310
What is a dynamical
evolution of the system?

00:00:59.310 --> 00:01:01.100
How does the atomic
wave function

00:01:01.100 --> 00:01:09.020
evolve when we couple two
states using optical fields?

00:01:09.020 --> 00:01:15.230
And well, as usual, we start
with the basic phenomena.

00:01:15.230 --> 00:01:17.720
And this is we do
perturbation theory

00:01:17.720 --> 00:01:20.500
with a dipole Hamiltonian.

00:01:20.500 --> 00:01:25.170
And we have done that on Monday.

00:01:25.170 --> 00:01:27.190
We've done perturbation theory.

00:01:27.190 --> 00:01:29.830
And I made an
important distinction

00:01:29.830 --> 00:01:34.570
between a monochromatic
case and [INAUDIBLE] case.

00:01:34.570 --> 00:01:38.190
The monochromatic case gave
us in perturbation theory

00:01:38.190 --> 00:01:39.640
this result.

00:01:39.640 --> 00:01:41.450
And if you stare
at it for a while,

00:01:41.450 --> 00:01:43.940
you see, well, these are
just Rabi oscillations.

00:01:43.940 --> 00:01:46.720
It's not the formula
of Rabi oscillations

00:01:46.720 --> 00:01:48.670
with the generalized
Rabi frequency

00:01:48.670 --> 00:01:51.650
and power broadening because
it's perturbation theory.

00:01:51.650 --> 00:01:55.160
So these are Rabi oscillations
in the perturbative limit.

00:01:55.160 --> 00:01:59.690
But also on Monday I showed
you that for interactions

00:01:59.690 --> 00:02:03.920
with monochromatic light, we can
just rewrite the Hamiltonian.

00:02:03.920 --> 00:02:06.800
That it not just looks
like, it is exactly

00:02:06.800 --> 00:02:12.670
the Hamiltonian for spin
1/2 in a magnetic field.

00:02:12.670 --> 00:02:15.090
And we have already
discussed the solution.

00:02:15.090 --> 00:02:17.611
So, therefore, we know for
monochromatic radiation,

00:02:17.611 --> 00:02:19.360
we can just go beyond
perturbation theory.

00:02:19.360 --> 00:02:21.380
We can solve it exactly.

00:02:21.380 --> 00:02:21.970
OK.

00:02:21.970 --> 00:02:24.675
So monochromatic
radiation we understand.

00:02:24.675 --> 00:02:29.910
At least as long as we have
just the coupling of the atom

00:02:29.910 --> 00:02:33.270
to a single mode of the
electromagnetic field.

00:02:33.270 --> 00:02:36.174
And now we come back
to the broadband case.

00:02:36.174 --> 00:02:38.340
I give a little bit more
of a summary and an outline

00:02:38.340 --> 00:02:40.690
after I finish the
broadband case.

00:02:40.690 --> 00:02:45.770
So what we have right now is
we have Rabi oscillations,

00:02:45.770 --> 00:02:48.310
which we derived
for a single mode.

00:02:48.310 --> 00:02:52.670
And the broadband case
is such that we now

00:02:52.670 --> 00:02:59.940
assume that we have a
spectrum of frequencies.

00:02:59.940 --> 00:03:03.620
And we assume that to be
flat and broad in a moment.

00:03:03.620 --> 00:03:06.580
And what we have to
do now is we have

00:03:06.580 --> 00:03:09.470
to substitute in
this formula the Rabi

00:03:09.470 --> 00:03:12.100
frequency by the electric field.

00:03:12.100 --> 00:03:15.200
And the electric field
becomes using the connection

00:03:15.200 --> 00:03:23.070
between electric field
and energy density,

00:03:23.070 --> 00:03:25.280
eventually the Rabi
frequency squared

00:03:25.280 --> 00:03:30.150
gets replaced by an integral
over the spectral density.

00:03:30.150 --> 00:03:31.800
It looks mathematically exact.

00:03:31.800 --> 00:03:33.650
But, of course,
you all recognize

00:03:33.650 --> 00:03:37.170
that I've made a very
important assumption here.

00:03:37.170 --> 00:03:39.630
Namely, that there is no
correlation whatsoever

00:03:39.630 --> 00:03:41.550
between the different
frequencies.

00:03:41.550 --> 00:03:45.400
Because by integrating
here, I'm just

00:03:45.400 --> 00:03:47.410
summing up the e
squares assuming

00:03:47.410 --> 00:03:50.034
that there's no interference,
no coherence, no correlation

00:03:50.034 --> 00:03:51.450
between the different
frequencies.

00:03:54.390 --> 00:03:59.840
OK, so with those
assumptions I can now just

00:03:59.840 --> 00:04:01.970
formulate the
mathematics exactly.

00:04:01.970 --> 00:04:06.080
I calculate now the probability
to be in the excited state

00:04:06.080 --> 00:04:10.550
by assuming we have this kind of
pertrubative Rabi oscillations

00:04:10.550 --> 00:04:12.500
at every frequency component.

00:04:12.500 --> 00:04:16.209
But we integrate
over all frequencies.

00:04:16.209 --> 00:04:17.790
Any questions?

00:04:17.790 --> 00:04:24.465
So now-- and this is where
I ended the last lecture.

00:04:27.730 --> 00:04:31.257
And there are actually now, this
is really an interesting case.

00:04:31.257 --> 00:04:32.840
I know I sometimes
spend a lot of time

00:04:32.840 --> 00:04:35.230
on sort of where
the math is simple,

00:04:35.230 --> 00:04:37.280
but the physics is
really interesting.

00:04:37.280 --> 00:04:41.440
So the probability to find
an atom in the excited state

00:04:41.440 --> 00:04:45.510
is now this function
which replaces,

00:04:45.510 --> 00:04:47.610
which are the
Rabit oscillations,

00:04:47.610 --> 00:04:51.290
convoluted integrated
over the spectral density.

00:04:51.290 --> 00:04:53.005
And now we have to
consider two cases.

00:04:56.490 --> 00:04:59.870
If this function is flat and
is spectrally very broad,

00:04:59.870 --> 00:05:03.030
we can pull it out
of the integral

00:05:03.030 --> 00:05:07.040
However, this function
here, which are your Rabi

00:05:07.040 --> 00:05:10.240
oscillations-- sine squared
of an [? augument ?] divided

00:05:10.240 --> 00:05:13.630
by the [? augument. ?] I've
plotted it here for you.

00:05:13.630 --> 00:05:16.900
This function is
actually very peculiar.

00:05:16.900 --> 00:05:20.660
It has a height of t square.

00:05:20.660 --> 00:05:23.280
If you're doing Taylor
Expansion for short times t.

00:05:23.280 --> 00:05:26.380
But the width is
t to the minus 1.

00:05:26.380 --> 00:05:29.570
So as time goes by, it
gets narrower, and taller,

00:05:29.570 --> 00:05:30.910
and taller.

00:05:30.910 --> 00:05:34.510
And if you take t squared by
t to the minus 1, you get t.

00:05:34.510 --> 00:05:38.530
So the integral
over it is just t.

00:05:38.530 --> 00:05:43.780
So in other words,
we have a function

00:05:43.780 --> 00:05:47.350
which goes as t square.

00:05:47.350 --> 00:05:49.430
But the integral is t.

00:05:49.430 --> 00:05:52.280
And if the width is so narrow
that the width doesn't really

00:05:52.280 --> 00:05:56.430
matter, we can say this function
has become a delta function.

00:05:56.430 --> 00:05:58.900
But the integral over
the function is t.

00:05:58.900 --> 00:06:01.530
So it becomes t times
the delta function.

00:06:01.530 --> 00:06:03.400
And now we the two
limiting cases.

00:06:07.960 --> 00:06:14.250
If very short times t-- this
Rabi oscillation function

00:06:14.250 --> 00:06:16.420
is extremely broad.

00:06:16.420 --> 00:06:19.250
And at infinitesimal
times t, it is

00:06:19.250 --> 00:06:22.120
broader than any
spectral bandwidths.

00:06:22.120 --> 00:06:23.870
So actually what we
are doing is when

00:06:23.870 --> 00:06:27.780
we solve this integral at very
short time, this is broader.

00:06:27.780 --> 00:06:30.000
And we pull this
out of the integral.

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:32.940
And this gives us a
prefect of t squared.

00:06:32.940 --> 00:06:35.053
So, therefore, the
excitation probability

00:06:35.053 --> 00:06:38.995
is t squared times the integral
of the spectral function which

00:06:38.995 --> 00:06:40.245
is just the totally intensity.

00:06:42.750 --> 00:06:46.810
However, if you
wait a little time,

00:06:46.810 --> 00:06:49.050
and eventually if
the time is such

00:06:49.050 --> 00:06:53.530
that the time is longer
than the inverse bandwidths

00:06:53.530 --> 00:06:58.290
of the spectral radiation,
then the spectral radiation

00:06:58.290 --> 00:07:01.470
is broader than
this function, f.

00:07:01.470 --> 00:07:04.150
And we pull this
out of the integral.

00:07:04.150 --> 00:07:07.270
And then what we have is we
have simply the integral here

00:07:07.270 --> 00:07:11.250
over the delta function
which gives us a factor of t.

00:07:11.250 --> 00:07:12.770
So we have two functions.

00:07:12.770 --> 00:07:15.910
And whichever is broader can
be pulled out of the integral.

00:07:15.910 --> 00:07:18.010
And that means in one
case, we have a probability

00:07:18.010 --> 00:07:21.090
which is t squared times
the total intensity.

00:07:21.090 --> 00:07:23.310
And in the other case,
we have a behavior

00:07:23.310 --> 00:07:27.270
which is the time times the
spectral density at 0 detuning.

00:07:33.440 --> 00:07:34.360
OK.

00:07:34.360 --> 00:07:38.180
So now let's-- just a side
remark before I interpret this

00:07:38.180 --> 00:07:42.590
result, this function you
would recover actually the Rabi

00:07:42.590 --> 00:07:43.330
oscillation.

00:07:43.330 --> 00:07:45.050
I plotted it in
that way emphasizing

00:07:45.050 --> 00:07:46.680
the amplitude and the width.

00:07:46.680 --> 00:07:51.150
But if you look for fixed
detuning and you vary the time,

00:07:51.150 --> 00:07:53.390
this function is
sort of spreading out

00:07:53.390 --> 00:07:56.580
and at a fixed detuning,
you'll go up and down.

00:07:56.580 --> 00:07:58.100
And these are the
Rabi oscillations

00:07:58.100 --> 00:08:02.720
we have discussed for
monochromatic radiation before.

00:08:02.720 --> 00:08:06.070
So these two limiting cases
are actually very important.

00:08:06.070 --> 00:08:09.830
At very short times, the
behavior is, you know,

00:08:09.830 --> 00:08:12.210
we have broad
spectral radiation.

00:08:12.210 --> 00:08:14.600
But if the time is shorter
than the inverse bandwidth

00:08:14.600 --> 00:08:17.630
of the radiation, even
the broadband radiation

00:08:17.630 --> 00:08:20.070
is like monochromatic wave.

00:08:20.070 --> 00:08:24.680
And the short time behavior is
t squared times the intensity.

00:08:24.680 --> 00:08:27.670
That's exactly what we got
for monochromatic light.

00:08:27.670 --> 00:08:30.256
In other words, if
you're broadening,

00:08:30.256 --> 00:08:31.630
you have a broad
spectral source,

00:08:31.630 --> 00:08:33.980
but if your inverse
time is broader

00:08:33.980 --> 00:08:36.020
than the broadening of
the spectral source,

00:08:36.020 --> 00:08:38.409
you're back to the
monochromatic case.

00:08:38.409 --> 00:08:40.030
So a lot of people get confused.

00:08:40.030 --> 00:08:43.370
I mean, I see that often
in part 3 oral exams, that

00:08:43.370 --> 00:08:45.080
no matter what your
spectral bandwidth

00:08:45.080 --> 00:08:47.050
is-- unless it's infinite.

00:08:47.050 --> 00:08:49.140
But let's discuss a
pathological case.

00:08:49.140 --> 00:08:52.530
For any broadband
light, at short moments,

00:08:52.530 --> 00:08:55.080
the system evolves as t square.

00:08:55.080 --> 00:08:59.050
And t square is the hallmark
of coherent time evolution.

00:08:59.050 --> 00:09:00.890
The amplitude goes with t.

00:09:00.890 --> 00:09:03.350
The probability
goes with t square.

00:09:03.350 --> 00:09:07.400
And only when the bandwidth
of the spectral light

00:09:07.400 --> 00:09:11.200
dominates when we can replace
this by the delta function.

00:09:11.200 --> 00:09:13.390
Then we are in the
regime, which you all

00:09:13.390 --> 00:09:18.350
know is Fermi's Golden Rule,
where we [INAUDIBLE] equation.

00:09:18.350 --> 00:09:20.540
And it all comes
from this formula.

00:09:20.540 --> 00:09:23.540
It all comes from assuming
Rabi oscillations.

00:09:23.540 --> 00:09:26.820
But then performing
the spectral integral

00:09:26.820 --> 00:09:28.380
over the Rabi oscillation.

00:09:28.380 --> 00:09:30.960
This takes us from
the narrowband case

00:09:30.960 --> 00:09:33.471
to the broadband case.

00:09:33.471 --> 00:09:34.800
Any questions about that?

00:09:34.800 --> 00:09:35.300
Yes?

00:09:35.300 --> 00:09:37.920
AUDIENCE: So what says
the bandwidth here?

00:09:37.920 --> 00:09:41.097
Because we assume
its narrowness arises

00:09:41.097 --> 00:09:42.680
just because of the
short [INAUDIBLE].

00:09:42.680 --> 00:09:44.140
PROFESSOR: I will
use an LED which

00:09:44.140 --> 00:09:45.860
has a few nanometer bandwidths.

00:09:45.860 --> 00:09:49.540
Use sunlight which has a few
hundred nanometer bandwidths.

00:09:49.540 --> 00:09:50.850
Whatever your light source is.

00:09:55.850 --> 00:09:57.930
At this point, it's
a general discussion.

00:09:57.930 --> 00:10:00.996
And I'm not going beyond
the two limiting cases here.

00:10:00.996 --> 00:10:02.870
Of course, if you have
a complicated spectral

00:10:02.870 --> 00:10:05.170
distribution, well,
you're on your own

00:10:05.170 --> 00:10:07.700
to solve this integral.

00:10:07.700 --> 00:10:09.895
But at short times,
we have this behavior.

00:10:09.895 --> 00:10:13.560
At long times, we have this.

00:10:13.560 --> 00:10:16.920
And the two regimes
are separated

00:10:16.920 --> 00:10:21.410
by the time where I have
a crossover in one case.

00:10:21.410 --> 00:10:24.310
This is broader and I can
pull it out in the other case.

00:10:24.310 --> 00:10:27.370
This function is broader and
I pull it out of the integral.

00:10:27.370 --> 00:10:29.480
And just where
this happens, this

00:10:29.480 --> 00:10:33.710
is where we have the transition
from t squared to t behavior.

00:10:33.710 --> 00:10:35.895
From coherent evolution
to rate equation.

00:10:49.790 --> 00:10:50.290
OK.

00:10:57.595 --> 00:10:58.095
Yes.

00:11:07.700 --> 00:11:11.230
So let's now look at the
situation of broadband light.

00:11:11.230 --> 00:11:13.600
Because later today I
want to discuss with you

00:11:13.600 --> 00:11:15.380
Einstein's a and b coefficient.

00:11:15.380 --> 00:11:17.860
A very classical topic
of atomic physics.

00:11:17.860 --> 00:11:20.980
A very famous concept
introduced by Einstein.

00:11:20.980 --> 00:11:23.870
And actually I want to use
the perturbation theory

00:11:23.870 --> 00:11:26.710
for broadband light which
we have now formulated

00:11:26.710 --> 00:11:30.120
to derive for you the b
coefficient of Einstein's a

00:11:30.120 --> 00:11:32.780
and b coefficient theory.

00:11:32.780 --> 00:11:33.280
OK.

00:11:33.280 --> 00:11:44.375
So for large time, we
can now talk about rate.

00:11:49.450 --> 00:11:54.420
Which is the probability
which increases linearly

00:11:54.420 --> 00:11:58.180
with time per unit time.

00:11:58.180 --> 00:12:04.160
And this was the
matrix element squared.

00:12:04.160 --> 00:12:08.470
2 epsilon 0 h-bar squared, 2 pi.

00:12:08.470 --> 00:12:10.260
The 2 cancels.

00:12:10.260 --> 00:12:14.690
And then we have from the delta
function, the spectral density

00:12:14.690 --> 00:12:15.690
at 0 detuning.

00:12:18.330 --> 00:12:20.755
Which is the spectral density
at the resonance frequency.

00:12:27.570 --> 00:12:30.250
So we have a rate equation now.

00:12:30.250 --> 00:12:33.760
That the rate equation
is the b coefficient.

00:12:33.760 --> 00:12:39.240
Einstein's famous b coefficient
times the spectral density.

00:12:39.240 --> 00:12:44.530
And the b coefficient is
now the proportionality

00:12:44.530 --> 00:12:48.640
constant between in
the equation above.

00:12:48.640 --> 00:12:53.280
Which is pi d squared.

00:12:53.280 --> 00:12:57.500
But now in all the formula
for the b coefficient,

00:12:57.500 --> 00:12:59.790
there's a factor of 3.

00:12:59.790 --> 00:13:04.770
Because the assumption is made
that we have isotropy of space.

00:13:04.770 --> 00:13:07.160
The atom are randomly oriented.

00:13:07.160 --> 00:13:20.310
And, therefore, dx squared
for given polarization,

00:13:20.310 --> 00:13:23.230
the dipole moment projected on a
polarization of the light which

00:13:23.230 --> 00:13:27.462
is dx squared is just
1/3 of the absolute value

00:13:27.462 --> 00:13:28.670
of the dipole moment squared.

00:13:38.980 --> 00:13:41.640
So in other words,
just to remind you

00:13:41.640 --> 00:13:45.300
what I have actually
discussed is nothing else

00:13:45.300 --> 00:13:46.820
than Fermi's Golden Rule.

00:13:49.610 --> 00:13:53.030
And I could've reminded
you of Fermi's Golden Rule

00:13:53.030 --> 00:13:55.490
where the rate is given.

00:13:55.490 --> 00:13:58.330
I just use a standard
notation of textbooks.

00:13:58.330 --> 00:14:02.580
You take the matrix element
squared, you multiply by 2 pi,

00:14:02.580 --> 00:14:04.135
and then you have
a delta function.

00:14:06.780 --> 00:14:12.659
And the delta function implies
a delta function is always

00:14:12.659 --> 00:14:14.200
a reminder that it
needs integration.

00:14:18.740 --> 00:14:21.305
So whenever you have a delta
function in Fermi's Golden

00:14:21.305 --> 00:14:24.980
Rule, you have to integrate.

00:14:24.980 --> 00:14:26.760
And there are two possibilities.

00:14:26.760 --> 00:14:31.710
You have to integrate over the
spectrum of external fields.

00:14:31.710 --> 00:14:33.550
That's what we just did.

00:14:33.550 --> 00:14:38.610
The other possibility is, which
doesn't apply to what we just

00:14:38.610 --> 00:14:41.350
discussed, that you
have to integrate over

00:14:41.350 --> 00:14:43.120
a continuum of final states.

00:14:48.120 --> 00:14:50.790
This will be important when
we use a Fermi's Golden Rule

00:14:50.790 --> 00:14:53.350
expression to talk about
spontaneous emission

00:14:53.350 --> 00:14:56.574
where we have a continuum
of final states.

00:14:56.574 --> 00:14:57.990
So anyway, I could
have just said,

00:14:57.990 --> 00:14:59.700
let's start with
Fermi's Golden Rule

00:14:59.700 --> 00:15:02.030
and let's jump to
the final result.

00:15:02.030 --> 00:15:04.990
But I really wanted
to emphasize here

00:15:04.990 --> 00:15:08.880
the sort of intimate connection
between Rabi oscillation,

00:15:08.880 --> 00:15:11.090
the t square
dependence, and how this

00:15:11.090 --> 00:15:12.730
turns into a rate equation.

00:15:22.500 --> 00:15:25.030
OK.

00:15:25.030 --> 00:15:33.106
Let's just summarize what
we have done in a table.

00:15:36.600 --> 00:15:42.955
We have seen two
different regime.

00:15:47.880 --> 00:15:50.990
In one case with
the Rabi resonance,

00:15:50.990 --> 00:16:01.850
we are discussing a single
final state of the atom.

00:16:01.850 --> 00:16:06.720
A single mode of the
electromagnetic field.

00:16:06.720 --> 00:16:11.070
All energy levels, all
states are discrete.

00:16:11.070 --> 00:16:18.650
We are talking about unitary
reversible time evolution.

00:16:18.650 --> 00:16:21.650
When we had rate
equations, we are

00:16:21.650 --> 00:16:25.750
talking about many final states.

00:16:25.750 --> 00:16:27.720
We integrate over them.

00:16:27.720 --> 00:16:36.870
Or and/or many modes
of the external field.

00:16:36.870 --> 00:16:39.750
