00:25:58.540 --> 00:26:05.590
which many people in this
class use for a living, this

00:26:05.590 --> 00:26:07.340
is actually part
of this equation.

00:26:07.340 --> 00:26:10.410
Because the equilibrium
between-- again,

00:26:10.410 --> 00:26:12.970
I discuss here Einstein's
a and b coefficient--

00:26:12.970 --> 00:26:17.410
the equilibrium between
the electronic structure,

00:26:17.410 --> 00:26:20.060
the ground and excited
state with a photon field.

00:26:20.060 --> 00:26:22.740
But Einstein also
considered the equilibrium

00:26:22.740 --> 00:26:25.360
between the motional
degree of the atom.

00:26:25.360 --> 00:26:27.390
And equilibrium between
the motional degree

00:26:27.390 --> 00:26:29.800
of the atom and
the radiation field

00:26:29.800 --> 00:26:33.140
requires the spontaneous force.

00:26:33.140 --> 00:26:35.830
The spontaneous radiation force.

00:26:35.830 --> 00:26:38.120
I'm not discussing it here.

00:26:38.120 --> 00:26:42.580
But I'm discussing here is now
an equilibrium between ground

00:26:42.580 --> 00:26:44.250
state and excited state.

00:26:56.450 --> 00:27:03.520
So the probability to find
an atom in the excited state

00:27:03.520 --> 00:27:10.390
is simply described by
the Boltzmann factor.

00:27:13.470 --> 00:27:15.450
Now it's traditional
in the discussion

00:27:15.450 --> 00:27:16.960
of Einstein's a
and b coefficient

00:27:16.960 --> 00:27:24.260
to allow for degeneracy factors
at ground and excited state.

00:27:24.260 --> 00:27:27.620
I have to say I
usually hate that I

00:27:27.620 --> 00:27:28.960
try not to talk about levels.

00:27:28.960 --> 00:27:30.900
I just talk about
quantum states.

00:27:30.900 --> 00:27:33.800
Non-degenerate individual
quantum states.

00:27:33.800 --> 00:27:36.720
So in that sense, I try
to characterize population

00:27:36.720 --> 00:27:39.070
in a quantum state,
not in a level.

00:27:39.070 --> 00:27:42.230
But it is standard to
follow Einstein's concept

00:27:42.230 --> 00:27:44.270
where we have degeneracies.

00:27:44.270 --> 00:27:47.920
I'm not emphasizing them
here, but I will just

00:27:47.920 --> 00:27:50.610
write them down
where they belong.

00:27:50.610 --> 00:27:52.430
OK, so this takes care.

00:27:52.430 --> 00:27:58.240
We know what is a fraction of
atoms in the excited state.

00:27:58.240 --> 00:28:00.890
So this is the equilibrium.

00:28:00.890 --> 00:28:10.720
The next thing we
need is the light.

00:28:10.720 --> 00:28:14.080
And Einstein assumed that
it's a spectral density

00:28:14.080 --> 00:28:15.740
in a black-body cavity.

00:28:21.010 --> 00:28:27.710
So we need the energy density
per frequency interval.

00:28:27.710 --> 00:28:31.210
And this is nothing else
than the occupation number

00:28:31.210 --> 00:28:36.730
of the mode times the
energy of the photon.

00:28:36.730 --> 00:28:41.185
Times the density of states.

00:28:46.630 --> 00:28:50.360
The photon number
per mode is just

00:28:50.360 --> 00:28:57.650
given by the
Bose-Einstein factor.

00:28:57.650 --> 00:29:01.040
Bose-Einstein statistics factor.

00:29:01.040 --> 00:29:10.710
The mode density is, as you
know, in three dimension.

00:29:10.710 --> 00:29:14.720
Omega squared, pi
square over c cube.

00:29:19.950 --> 00:29:28.470
So, therefore, the spectral
density of black-body radiation

00:29:28.470 --> 00:29:33.430
has-- and we need that,
and omega cube dependence.

00:29:38.180 --> 00:29:47.380
And then it has this
Bose-Einstein denominator

00:29:47.380 --> 00:29:48.810
in the well-known form.

00:29:48.810 --> 00:29:52.460
So this is now Planck's
black-body spectrum

00:29:52.460 --> 00:29:54.190
in the units where we need it.

00:29:57.410 --> 00:30:07.110
So all we need is now to find
the famous Einstein a and b

00:30:07.110 --> 00:30:08.090
coefficient.

00:30:08.090 --> 00:30:11.270
We have to write down a
rate equation for the atoms.

00:30:17.660 --> 00:30:20.820
So the fact is we know
already what equilibrium is.

00:30:20.820 --> 00:30:23.050
Excited state versus
ground state population

00:30:23.050 --> 00:30:24.310
is the Boltzmann factor.

00:30:24.310 --> 00:30:26.100
But now we write
down a rate equation

00:30:26.100 --> 00:30:28.040
which involves a
black-body field.

00:30:28.040 --> 00:30:31.410
And then we compare the
solution of the rate equation

00:30:31.410 --> 00:30:33.520
to the solution we already know.

00:30:33.520 --> 00:30:37.170
And from that, we get
Einstein's a and b coefficient.

00:30:37.170 --> 00:30:47.860
OK, so the change in the
population of the excited state

00:30:47.860 --> 00:30:51.270
has three different terms.

00:30:51.270 --> 00:30:58.360
One is the energy density
of the black-body radiation

00:30:58.360 --> 00:31:04.080
can cause stimulated emission.

00:31:11.004 --> 00:31:12.920
So, therefore, it's
proportional to the number

00:31:12.920 --> 00:31:14.460
of atoms in the excited state.

00:31:20.140 --> 00:31:22.480
The energy density of
the black-body radiation

00:31:22.480 --> 00:31:25.464
can cause absorption.

00:31:25.464 --> 00:31:26.880
This is proportional
to the number

00:31:26.880 --> 00:31:28.280
of atoms in the ground state.

00:31:44.190 --> 00:31:49.800
And then this
equation as it stands

00:31:49.800 --> 00:31:51.700
would lead to contradiction
when I compare

00:31:51.700 --> 00:31:55.040
the solution of this equation to
the Boltzmann factor we already

00:31:55.040 --> 00:31:56.220
know.

00:31:56.220 --> 00:32:01.800
And the only way to fix it
is to add an extra term.

00:32:01.800 --> 00:32:03.450
Which is spontaneous emission.

00:32:06.710 --> 00:32:09.800
If spontaneous emission
were not necessary,

00:32:09.800 --> 00:32:13.550
this a coefficient could in
the end turn out to be 0.

00:32:13.550 --> 00:32:15.320
Or it can be undetermined.

00:32:15.320 --> 00:32:18.355
But as we see, it is
necessary for consistency.

00:32:22.760 --> 00:32:25.955
So this is pretty much
the famous rate equation.

00:32:34.790 --> 00:32:38.005
And we are interested in
the equilibrium solution.

00:32:41.850 --> 00:32:50.640
In equilibrium, all
derivatives vanish.

00:32:50.640 --> 00:33:02.120
And then by setting
the derivatives to 0,

00:33:02.120 --> 00:33:03.980
I have one equation.

00:33:03.980 --> 00:33:11.970
And I will rewrite the equation
by putting the spectral density

00:33:11.970 --> 00:33:13.740
of the light on one side.

00:33:17.450 --> 00:33:19.280
And everything else
on the other side.

00:33:19.280 --> 00:33:22.976
And what we have here
is the a coefficient.

00:33:26.650 --> 00:33:30.660
The ground state population,
the excited state population.

00:33:30.660 --> 00:33:31.423
The b coefficient.

00:33:40.910 --> 00:33:43.570
So this is the spectral
density of-- it's

00:33:43.570 --> 00:33:46.340
just an expression for
the spectral density.

00:33:46.340 --> 00:33:52.570
We want to put in now that
the excited state fraction is

00:33:52.570 --> 00:33:55.640
given by a Boltzmann factor.

00:33:55.640 --> 00:34:04.650
So, therefore, Ne over Ng
becomes the Boltzmann factor.

00:34:04.650 --> 00:34:07.310
And, yes, there are
these degeneracy factors.

00:34:12.320 --> 00:34:15.060
So I've pretty much divided the
denominator and the numerator

00:34:15.060 --> 00:34:18.120
by the population in
the excited state.

00:34:18.120 --> 00:34:21.350
And here I get Beg

00:34:21.350 --> 00:34:26.170
OK, so this is the result
for the spectral density.

00:34:26.170 --> 00:34:31.409
But we know already that
the spectral density

00:34:31.409 --> 00:34:33.570
has to be of the Planck form.

00:34:33.570 --> 00:34:35.870
So now we can
simply compare what

00:34:35.870 --> 00:34:39.170
we know to what we obtained
from the rate equation

00:34:39.170 --> 00:34:41.435
and make sure that it matches.

00:34:44.139 --> 00:34:53.580
So it's good we have
the exponential factor.

00:34:53.580 --> 00:34:57.580
And by bringing this
expression to the form

00:34:57.580 --> 00:34:59.720
of the other
expression, we actually

00:34:59.720 --> 00:35:02.730
have to fulfill two conditions.

00:35:02.730 --> 00:35:07.060
One is in order to
make sure that kind

00:35:07.060 --> 00:35:10.440
of the total expression is
OK, it gives us a ratio.

00:35:10.440 --> 00:35:12.290
The Planck body
spectrum is normalized.

00:35:12.290 --> 00:35:14.080
There is no unknown prefactor.

00:35:14.080 --> 00:35:17.250
So this determines
the ratio of a and b.

00:35:17.250 --> 00:35:21.910
And also since we have
this functional form

00:35:21.910 --> 00:35:23.730
of the Bose-Einstein
statistics which

00:35:23.730 --> 00:35:25.930
has this exponential
factor minus 1,

00:35:25.930 --> 00:35:29.640
it gives us also a relation
between the 2B coefficient.

